This year’s Launch Your Career Conference, in Collaboration with Yielding Accomplished African Women, we are proud to announce the She Solves Hackathon: From Ideas to Solutions.  We invite all Black College Women to join us solve pressing issues that affect black women using Data Science and Machine Learning👩🏽‍💻.  And don’t worry if you don’t have any skills in data science as that’s the goal of this hackathon. It’s an opportunity to learn a new skill, while solving problems. Sounds fun right🤩?  Further details of the Hackathon will be shared during the Launch Your Career Conference, and it will officially begin right after the conference spanning a 1 week period.  The winners 🏆 will be announced and recognized during the International Women’s Day Celebration in March.  Get ready for this amazing challenge. It promises to be exciting.  If you missed the registration deadline for Launch, don’t worry join our waitlist and you can still be admitted. Sign up now here or with the link in our bio: http://linktr.ee/accomplishedafricanwomen  Don’t be left out📌  #yaaw #WIML #spreadtheword #yaashedid #tech #finance #blackcollegewomen #womenempowerment #womenintech #datascience #blackhistorymonth #knust #unilag #ug #hbcus 7m

Ever wondered why you dream? Neuroscientists think that human brains can suffer from overfitting, just like your models. Researchers say we dream to introduce 'noise' or bad data into our models of reality, which keeps us from making bad mental predictions. Or as they put it: "The purpose of dreaming is to provide 'out-of-distribution' simulations specifically to prevent overfitting and improve generalisation.” So next time you have a crazy dream, just think: your brain is keeping itself working properly.  Read More👉https://zcu.io/aMG9

This #EarthDay, we want to share something we've been working on: an open-source model to predict air quality in Africa. We found that data on air quality is almost completely lacking for African cities, and we wanted to change that. Thanks to the amazing Zindians taking part in our #ZindiWeekendz hackathons, we can now share a tool to help African policymakers and public health experts predict how air quality will affect public health. During the #COVID19 pandemic, we hope a tool like this can even help save lives. Healthy air, healthy planet, healthy people.   #opendata #machinelearning  Read More👉https://zcu.io/ve8A

Africa’s growth and development is inextricably linked to the development of the agricultural sector!   Zindi is challenging data scientists to build machine learning models that predict soil humidity for agricultural plots, enabling farmers to efficiently manage their water usage. The data for the challenge was collected by Wazihub (https://zcu.io/l8hq) in maize and peanut farms in Senegal using low-cost internet of things (IoT) sensors.
